sh — OCOS shell

SYNOPSIS
  sh [-c "SCRIPT"]
  sh

DESCRIPTION
  Interactive shell with pipes, redirects, control flow and POSIX-style
  quoting.

  Pipes / redirects / control flow:
    cmd1 | cmd2          stdout of cmd1 → stdin of cmd2
    cmd > file           write stdout to file (truncate)
    cmd >> file          append stdout to file
    cmd < file           read stdin from file
    cmd 2> file          redirect stderr
    cmd1 && cmd2         run cmd2 only if cmd1 succeeded
    cmd1 || cmd2         run cmd2 only if cmd1 failed
    cmd1 ; cmd2          run sequentially regardless

  Variables: $VAR, ${VAR}, $? (last status). Set with `set K=V`.

  Tab completion: first word completes against $PATH + builtins;
  subsequent words complete file/directory paths under PWD.

  History: stored at $HOME/.sh_history, persistent across reboots.

  Editor key bindings:
    Ctrl-A / Home       jump to start of line
    Ctrl-E / End        jump to end of line
    Ctrl-W              delete previous word
    Ctrl-U              clear the line
    Ctrl-K              kill to end of line
    Ctrl-L              redraw the prompt
    Ctrl-C              abort the current line (does not exit)
    Ctrl-D              EOF on an empty line

  Builtins: cd, pwd, exit, set, unset, alias, unalias, echo, true,
  false, exec, export. Everything else is resolved through $PATH
  (default /bin) using either /bin/<name>.lua or /bin/<name>.

EXAMPLES
  echo hi | grep h
  ls /etc | wc -l
  if=$(cat /etc/hostname); echo "host=$if"

SEE ALSO
  lua(1), help(1)
